message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The patient had a history of cervical cancer, and now presents with postmenopausal bleeding and an irregular mass protruding from the vaginal wall, which suggests metastasis of cervical cancer via direct extension to the vagina. Atrophy of vaginal tissues and primary malignancy of vaginal squamous cells are less likely given the patient’s history. Hematogenous spread is less likely because the mass is directly related to the site of the original cancer.
